The representative N2 adsorption desorption isotherms and pore size distributions (Fig. 5
                     ) illustrate the surface area and porosity of Zn-NLw and Fe-NLw MOFs. Mesoporous structure could be observed from the mean pore size calculations of Zn-NLw (6.4 nm) and Fe-NLw (3.6 nm). Also, Fe-NLw shows comparatively higher BET surface area (64.2 m2 g−1) than the Zn-NLw (9.8 m2 g−1), which could be attributed to the more accessibility of void space for the former, as the existence of a greater number of guest species or organic/inorganic impurities in the latter reduces entry of incoming N2 gas molecules. The slightly distorted isotherm (Type IV) observed for both structures further confirms the presence of entrapped ZnO or Fe3O4 molecules in between the pores [49]. As shown in Fig. 6
                     , the HRTEM images of Zn-NLw (Fig. 6a–c) exhibited uniform well-defined core-shell architecture with an average core diameter of 200 nm, while Fe-NLw displays distinct pores (Fig. 6d) with comparatively higher surface area, demonstrates their significant adsorption capacity. In most of the cases, the electron dense metal nodes dominate the contrast in TEM, making structural organic linkers invisible, that can be easily distinguished from the TEM images [50,51].

To demonstrate the efficacy of as-synthesized MOFs in biomolecule sensing and cellular imaging in vitro cytocompatibility evaluation was performed. The MTT assay data depicts the compatibility of the as-synthesized MOFs with the cells after their interaction for 24 and 72 h; the data is presented as (Fig. 9
                     A). Zn-NLw and Fe-NLw treated cells exhibited >80% cell viability even at a high dosage (80 μg mL−1) after 24 h of incubation. As the culture time passed (72 h), Zn-NLw and Fe-NLw exhibited viability percentages of 81.15 and 86.12%, respectively, even at a concentration of 60 μg mL−1, demonstrating the cytocompatibility of these samples. It is important to note that even at a high concentration (80 μg mL−1) for a treatment period of 72 h, Fe-NLw displayed 83.65% cell viability. The Prussian blue staining of HOS cells, performed as post-incubation analysis with Fe-NLw (20 μg mL−1), demonstrated evidence of the sample uptaken by the cells (Fig. 9B). Precisely, the dark blue spots in the cell cytoplasm of the treated cells (Fig. 9Bb & c) are attributed to the Prussian blue (ferric ferrocyanide) formed from the reaction of potassium ferrocyanide with the reactive ferric ion present in the MOF structure, which is absent in control (untreated) cells (Fig. 9Ba), representing the cellular uptake of Fe-NLw. In addition, there are no noticeable changes in the normal adhered morphology of the cells after uptake of the Fe-NLw, which further confirms the cytocompatible nature of the sample [34]. Cytoskeletal architectures of the cells were analyzed by F-actin and nuclear staining (DAPI). F-actin/DAPI staining of the cells post-incubation with Fe-NLw exhibited a clear picture of better cell-material interaction; the images are presented in (Fig. 10
                     ). The untreated control cells exhibited a normal arrangement of the actin cytoskeleton with typical nuclear morphology. Similar results were observed in Zn-NLw and Fe-NLw; that is, there are no visible deformations of actin microfilaments after the treatment at the given concentration (20 μg mL−1). The viability of the treated cells was further quantitatively determined from live dead assay using FDA and PI showing distinction of live cell population from the population of dead cells (Fig. S5). The fluorescent images show evidence for the higher number of live cells for both Zn-NLw and Fe-NLw with comparatively better percentage for the latter (Fig. S5d).
